WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.160
[Amit Varma]: There is this glib takedown of a saying, there are two kinds of people in the world, those

00:00:10.160 --> 00:00:12.960
[Amit Varma]: who think there are two kinds of people in the world and those who don't.

00:00:12.960 --> 00:00:18.120
[Amit Varma]: I'm wary of generalizing, but I will add to this list of false dichotomies by speculating

00:00:18.120 --> 00:00:21.840
[Amit Varma]: that there might be two kinds of people in the world, those given to self reflection

00:00:21.840 --> 00:00:24.160
[Amit Varma]: and those who do not reflect on themselves.

00:00:24.160 --> 00:00:26.440
[Amit Varma]: Now there's obviously a continuum between the two.

00:00:26.440 --> 00:00:31.080
[Amit Varma]: So it's perhaps better to talk of the tendency to self reflect, which exists in a lesser

00:00:31.080 --> 00:00:33.200
[Amit Varma]: or greater degree in most people.

00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:36.160
[Amit Varma]: When I was younger, I was not given much to self reflection.

00:00:36.160 --> 00:00:41.000
[Amit Varma]: I never got meta about myself as it were, I was sure of the talents I had, blind so

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:45.760
[Amit Varma]: often to my good fortune, unaware of how my character was shaped so often by things outside

00:00:45.760 --> 00:00:48.200
[Amit Varma]: of me, even unaware of my own character.

00:00:48.200 --> 00:00:52.880
[Amit Varma]: I didn't think about why I wanted what I wanted, and why I reacted to events around me the

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:53.880
[Amit Varma]: way I did.

00:00:53.880 --> 00:00:58.260
[Amit Varma]: I'd like to think that I know myself a bit better now than I did then, but perhaps not

00:00:58.260 --> 00:00:59.760
[Amit Varma]: as well as I could.

00:00:59.760 --> 00:01:03.280
[Amit Varma]: And in life, I see people who do no self reflection at all.

00:01:03.280 --> 00:01:08.080
[Amit Varma]: And those who do examine themselves, and in doing so can point me to truths about myself

00:01:08.080 --> 00:01:09.080
[Amit Varma]: as well.

00:01:09.080 --> 00:01:14.240
[Amit Varma]: That is why I love reading memoirs, a good memoir, by definition, is a reflection on

00:01:14.240 --> 00:01:15.240
[Amit Varma]: the self.

00:01:15.240 --> 00:01:18.780
[Amit Varma]: And that's true of the wonderful memoir written by my guest today.

00:01:18.780 --> 00:01:22.600
[Amit Varma]: This is also why I love being able to have the long conversations that I have on the

00:01:22.600 --> 00:01:23.600
[Amit Varma]: show.

00:01:23.600 --> 00:01:28.360
[Amit Varma]: Because my guests trust me enough to open themselves up to me and to speak without filters.

00:01:28.360 --> 00:01:32.480
[Amit Varma]: And most of the time, they give me a lot to think about, even after they've gone home,

00:01:32.480 --> 00:01:34.880
[Amit Varma]: and the mics are off, and all is silent.

00:01:34.880 --> 00:01:39.960
[Unknown]: Have you also felt that way?

00:01:39.960 --> 00:01:45.160
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:01:45.160 --> 00:01:46.160
[Unknown]: science.

00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:52.600
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:52.600 --> 00:01:53.760
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene in the unseen.

00:01:53.760 --> 00:01:57.800
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is a legendary cricket journalist and editor, Pradeep magazine.

00:01:57.800 --> 00:02:02.240
[Amit Varma]: When I started off in cricket journalism in the early 2000s, Pradeep was already one of

00:02:02.240 --> 00:02:06.520
[Amit Varma]: the most respected figures in the game, and was sports editor of the Hindustan Times.

00:02:06.520 --> 00:02:08.680
[Amit Varma]: I didn't get to know him too well in those days.

00:02:08.680 --> 00:02:12.760
[Amit Varma]: But I heard a lot about how he kickstarted the careers of so many young writers by giving

00:02:12.760 --> 00:02:16.320
[Amit Varma]: them jobs and mentoring them, teaching them his craft.

00:02:16.320 --> 00:02:19.880
[Amit Varma]: In the decades before this, he had been a fearless cricket writer, writing a book on

00:02:19.880 --> 00:02:24.320
[Amit Varma]: match fixing that began in 1997 and came out in 1999.

00:02:24.320 --> 00:02:27.680
[Amit Varma]: And you'll remember the match fixing scandal really broke in 2000.

00:02:27.680 --> 00:02:29.560
[Amit Varma]: He was so far ahead of his time.

00:02:29.560 --> 00:02:32.280
[Amit Varma]: The book he wrote then was called Not Quite Cricket.

00:02:32.280 --> 00:02:36.320
[Amit Varma]: His latest book, which I love reading, is called Not Just Cricket, a reporter's journey

00:02:36.320 --> 00:02:37.600
[Amit Varma]: through modern India.

00:02:37.600 --> 00:02:39.720
[Amit Varma]: It has all the qualities of a good memoir.

00:02:39.720 --> 00:02:44.500
[Amit Varma]: It has self reflection, and it tells a story not just of the writer, but also of the times

00:02:44.500 --> 00:02:45.500
[Amit Varma]: he lived in.

00:02:45.500 --> 00:02:49.920
[Amit Varma]: It gave me a lot to think about, not least of which was the role of serendipity in our

00:02:49.920 --> 00:02:50.920
[Amit Varma]: lives.

00:02:50.920 --> 00:02:53.280
[Amit Varma]: I'm sure you'll enjoy the conversation as much as I did.

00:02:53.280 --> 00:02:56.760
[Amit Varma]: But before we get to it, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:02:56.760 --> 00:03:00.520
[Amit Varma]: Do you want to read more?

